Europe needs immigrants to revitalize it
Brussels—More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for safe ports all summer to land the passengers on board.
Refugees and migrants on the Greek island of Lesbos, as well as other accommodation camps in Libya, are overcrowded.
Turkey has撕毁ed the 2016 agreement that aimed to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help migrants and its respect for international law, it does not want to be overwhelmed.
2015-16 saw a significant increase in the number of refugees and migrants flooding into the EU — many had fled the Syrian war — which greatly impacted trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded government confidence in managing the EU's external borders and asylum, also highlighting the ineffective cooperation with countries of origin.
Therefore, immigration became a political football, a favorite tool of populists.
Under President von der Leyen, the new EU Commission must重新控移民问题 while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to reorient its policies in four key areas and mobilize member states to act in the interest of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Any country where people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource external border control to a single state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, also a national one.
The EU Border and Coast Guard agency Frontex must be further reinforced and should deploy joint patrols with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to address economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Merging them has already brought the asylum system close to collapse; addressing them separately would help ensure that migrants concerned for their safety can speak up with their rights protected.
Solving the EU's genuine economic and social needs requires an effective blue or green card policy for economic migrants, along with the implementation of overall migration targets.
These mechanisms cannot be introduced only when the next migration crisis arises.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboos.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly identify which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must identify what assistance from the EU is needed to facilitate smooth migration processes.
Finally, visas and work permits must be made available to facilitate the return of irregular migrants to their countries of origin.
Certainly.
However, if governments were to agree on overall EU migration targets, it would be a significant step forward.
Conversely, member states can specify the countries of origin they want for economic migrants and the specific requirements, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
Thus, migration intake would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long had an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skills, and age groups.
Europe could do the same.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, it is necessary to abandon the一刀切 requirement for the mandatory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it may still be feasible if the border, asylum, and migration systems are sufficiently effective.
Moreover, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states will solve the problem of irregular migrants crossing external borders alone.
Shelters are already overcrowded, migrants are abused by authorities or pushed northward.
The responsibility of the first member state to which migrants arrive must be supplemented by EU cohesion.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can decisions made by individual countries be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the Schengen area for cross-border travel.
After streamlining the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies, the processing procedures for asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should foster stronger win-win cooperation with countries of origin and transit.
To deport migrants who are legally barred from entering the EU to their countries of origin, such connections are crucial.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
EU migration goals, along with skill cooperation to prepare jobs for Europe, can be offered to third countries seeking stable remittances.
Meanwhile, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and shortages of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
This success could make investments more secure, unleash private and domestic finance, thereby driving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives for migrants.
The new EU Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from unconscious reactions to migration crises and toward a more consistent and sustained approach, both internally and externally.
We must not miss this opportunity.
